        content:
          'The experience modification rate, commonly called the experience mod or EMR, is a multiplier that adjusts your premium based on your actual claims history compared to the expected losses for businesses of similar size and industry. A mod of 1.00 means your loss experience is exactly average. A mod below 1.00 indicates better-than-average experience and results in a premium credit, while a mod above 1.00 indicates worse-than-average experience and results in a surcharge.\n\nThe mod is calculated using three years of loss history, excluding the most recent policy year. Both claim frequency and severity are factored in, but the formula places more weight on frequency because multiple smaller claims are viewed as a stronger predictor of future losses than a single large event. This means that having several small claims can damage your mod more than one larger claim of the same total value.\n\nManaging your experience mod is one of the most effective ways to control workers compensation costs over the long term. A business with a 0.75 mod pays twenty-five percent less than a business with a 1.00 mod for the same payroll and classification, while a business with a 1.30 mod pays thirty percent more. Claim frequency reduction, aggressive return-to-work programs, and proper classification are the primary levers for improving your mod over time.',
